<dl id="n14067e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14067e">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14067e"> 67(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> gnosis / <font color="green">[??]</font></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><i><mark>Gnosis</i> was originally associated with knowledge | relating to the <i>inner</i> conditions, or World of Ideas, and served to elucidate the esoteric basis of Religion in contradistinction to &ldquo;Pistik,&rdquo; which was applied to the exoteric and popular Belief&mdash;the &ldquo;edifice&rdquo; erected by the church for the purpose of imparting instruction. There were &ldquo;heathen&rdquo;&mdash;that is, <i>pre</i>-Christian&mdash;as well as Christian Gnostics. The Manich&aelig;ans were Gnostics who united the ancient mysteries of Persia with Christian occult teachings. In the same way there were Jewish, Greek, Syrian, and Egyptian Gnostics, so named according to the mysteries which they had made their special field of research. <small> Ernst Boldt, <a name="BFLS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BFLS"><cite title="source">From Luther to Steiner</cite></a>, (1921) 131-2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
